-O0
When comparing optimization levels, the -O0 optimization level means no optimization was done by the compiler. 
The assembly generated will usually look very similar to the original C program. 
Additionally, the compiler does not try to make the code run faster and will typically store variables on the stack in memory.

-O1
At -O1 optimization, the compiler will usually clean up any redundant instructions.
The compiler also keeps some values in the registers instead of constantly storing them in memory.
The compiler typically stores the values in %rbx, %rbp, %r12, %r13, and %r14.

-O3
At -O3 optimization, the compiler uses a more aggressive optimization approach to make the program run faster. 
Additionally, this aggressive approach uses alignment instructions which is apparent in the dump_3.s file where we see line 17 using .p2align and so on. 
The compiler also optimized the ASCII check on line 46 in the project3.c file. 
The compiler used:
leal	-32(%rdi), %eax
cmpb	$94, %al

This means instead of checking byte >= 32 and byte <= 126, the compiler does byte - 32 <= 94.
Practically making the range 0-94 instead of 32-126
